ry cycle, this dumdum obvious observation is worth making anyway, if only t=
o capture the sheer strangeness of moments like this one=E2=80=94where any =
citizen who gives the slightest shit about the future of the country appear=
s to be fixated on tomorrow=E2=80=99s debate between <b>Kamala Harris</b> a=
nd <b>Donald Trump</b>, while many of the people most deeply embroiled in t=
he orchestration and conduct of their campaigns have already cast their gaz=
e beyond it. <br/><br/>This will be Harris and Trump=E2=80=99s first meetin=
g=E2=80=94not just on a debate stage or as political rivals, but literally =
their first in-the-flesh encounter <i>ever</i>.
It=E2=80=99s true, of course, that the public, the national media, and both=
 campaigns fully (and correctly) concur that the debate is a big fucking de=
al. But in the Harris and Trump high commands and their affiliated war room=
s, as well as at the higher strata of the political class writ large, there=
=E2=80=99s also an awareness that whatever happens on Tuesday night=E2=80=
=94barring another <b>Biden</b>-esque train derailment=E2=80=94on Wednesday=
 morning, both sides will need to come flying out of the blocks for the eig=
ht-week sprint to Election Day. <br/><br/>With that in mind, let=E2=80=99s =
take an informed gander inside the brain pans of the folks steering Teams H=
arris and Trump and the wider sphere of Democratic and Republican political=
 professionals. Amazingly, though their perspectives on the key variables t=
hat will decide the election differ dramatically, there=E2=80=99s a strikin=
g level of agreement about the variables themselves: the debate, for sure, =
but also five other factors: the calendar, the map,
the numbers, the filter, and the wild cards.<br/></td>
