x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The indictments com=
ing down from the Justice Department over the Russian campaign to influence=
 right-wing media were a reminder of a fundamental reality: Russia and Chin=
a are the most powerful forces besides the U.S. in geopolitics, and both wo=
uld rather see Trump as president than Harris. (Iran, which seemingly would=
 prefer Harris, was allegedly behind the recent cyberattack targeting Trump=
=2E) The likelihood that, in the wee=
ks leading up to the election, we=E2=80=
=99re going to see various forms of state and non-state information warfare=
 designed to upend the American election, according to experts, is extremel=
y high. Both campaigns are thinking about this all the time, but there=E2=
=80=99s a chance we will look back on this election six months from now and=
 recognize that the indictment was the first sign of something that metasta=
sized and became a dominant
factor in the homestretch of the race.<br/><br/>Another wild card is what m=
ay be a realignment of power in the Trump campaign. Of course, there=E2=80=
=99s never been an organization Donald Trump has led that hasn=E2=80=99t be=
en fractious, chaotic, and leaky. But <b>Susie Wiles </b>and <b>Chris</b> <=
b>LaCivita</b> are serious people, and they have been able to keep a relati=
vely firm grip on the rudder because of how comfortable everyone was runnin=
g against Biden. The test of the campaign is not when things are going well=
, but how well the organization performs when things get rocky. In the summ=
ers of both 2016 and 2020, Trump fired key people on his campaigns. This ti=
me, Trump <i>had</i> a stable organization run by political professionals f=
or many months, but now the old gang=E2=80=94most notably, <b>Corey Lewando=
wski</b>=E2=80=94are being summoned back into service. If <b>Steve Bannon</=
b> wasn=E2=80=99t presently in the hoosegow, I=E2=80=99d bet dollars to don=
uts he=E2=80=99d headed for Mar-a-Lago in 3=E2=80=A6 2=E2=80=A6
1.<br/> <br/>The much bigger problem is Trump=E2=80=99s blindingly obvious =
incapacities as a candidate in 2024. It=E2=80=99s not just that he isn=E2=
=80=99t great, or good. It=E2=80=99s that he=E2=80=99s a human train wreck.=
 In the end, Trump <i>is</i> his campaign. Republicans continue to nurse th=
e fantasy that Trump will somehow pull it together and find the wherewithal=
 to behave as he did for the last 14 days of the 2016 election, when he stu=
ck to the talking points that Bannon and <b>Kellyanne Conway </b>armed him =
with=E2=80=94and won. Can he do it again? Anything=E2=80=99s possible, I su=
ppose, and in the Trump era, the inconceivable has had a tendency to occur =
with shocking regularity. But old age and diminished faculties come for all=
 of us eventually, and the last one to know is the geezer in question. Just=
 ask Joe Biden.<br/></td>
